[[uid=830lw9b0]] FIRST ACT
[[uid=830lw9b1]] SCENE
[[uid=830lw9b2]]  [[ ]]  [[ ]]  [[ ]] [[attitudeInstr]] [[ ]]
[[uid=830lw9b3]] Morning-room in Algernon’s flat in [[ ]]
[[uid=830lw9b4]] Half-Moon Street. The room is
[[uid=830lw9b5]] luxuriously and artistically furnished. [[attitude]] [[newcode]]
[[uid=830lw9b6]] The sound of a piano is heard in the
[[uid=830lw9b7]] adjoining room.
[[uid=830lw9b8]] 
[[uid=830lw9b9]] [Lane is arranging afternoon tea on the
[[uid=830lw9bb]] table, and after the music has ceased,
[[uid=830lw9bc]] Algernon enters.]
[[uid=830lw9bd]] 
[[uid=830lw9bf]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9bg]] Did you hear what I was playing, Lane?
[[uid=830lw9bh]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9bj]] LANE.
[[uid=830lw9bk]] I didn’t think it polite to listen,
[[uid=830lw9bl]] sir.
[[uid=830lw9bm]] 
[[uid=830lw9bn]] ALGERNON. [[attitudeInstr]] [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9bp]] I’m sorry for that, for your sake. I
[[uid=830lw9bq]] don’t play accurately—any one can play
[[uid=830lw9br]] accurately—but I play with wonderful
[[uid=830lw9bs]] expression. As far as the piano is
[[uid=830lw9bt]] concerned, sentiment is my forte. I
[[uid=830lw9bw]] keep science for Life.
[[uid=830lw9bx]] 
[[uid=830lw9by]] LANE. [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9bz]] Yes, sir.
[[uid=830lw9c0]] 
[[uid=830lw9c1]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9c2]] And, speaking of the science of Life,
[[uid=830lw9c3]] have you got the cucumber sandwiches [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9c4]] cut for Lady Bracknell?
[[uid=830lw9c5]] 
[[uid=830lw9c6]] LANE.
[[uid=830lw9c7]] Yes, sir. [Hands them on a salver.]
[[uid=830lw9c8]] 
[[uid=830lw9c9]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9cb]] [Inspects them, takes two, and sits
[[uid=830lw9cc]] down on the sofa.] Oh! . . . by the
[[uid=830lw9cd]] way, Lane, I see from your book that on
[[uid=830lw9cf]] Thursday night, when Lord Shoreman and
[[uid=830lw9cg]] Mr. Worthing were dining with me, eight
[[uid=830lw9ch]] bottles of champagne are entered as
[[uid=830lw9cj]] having been consumed. [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9ck]] 
[[uid=830lw9cl]] LANE.
[[uid=830lw9cm]] Yes, sir; eight bottles and a pint.
[[uid=830lw9cn]] 
[[uid=830lw9cp]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9cq]] Why is it that at a bachelor’s [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9cr]] establishment the servants invariably [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9cs]] drink the champagne? I ask merely for
[[uid=830lw9ct]] information.
[[uid=830lw9cw]] 
[[uid=830lw9cx]] LANE.
[[uid=830lw9cy]] I attribute it to the superior quality
[[uid=830lw9cz]] of the wine, sir. I have often observed
[[uid=830lw9d0]] that in married households the
[[uid=830lw9d1]] champagne is rarely of a first-rate
[[uid=830lw9d2]] brand.
[[uid=830lw9d3]] 
[[uid=830lw9d4]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9d5]] Good heavens! Is marriage so
[[uid=830lw9d6]] demoralising as that?
[[uid=830lw9d7]] 
[[uid=830lw9d8]] LANE.
[[uid=830lw9d9]] I believe it is a very pleasant state,
[[uid=830lw9db]] sir. I have had very little experience
[[uid=830lw9dc]] of it myself up to the present. I have
[[uid=830lw9dd]] only been married once. That was in
[[uid=830lw9df]] consequence of a misunderstanding
[[uid=830lw9dg]] between myself and a young person.
[[uid=830lw9dh]] 
[[uid=830lw9dj]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9dk]] [Languidly.] I don’t know that I am
[[uid=830lw9dl]] much interested in your family life,
[[uid=830lw9dm]] Lane.
[[uid=830lw9dn]] 
[[uid=830lw9dp]] LANE.
[[uid=830lw9dq]] No, sir; it is not a very interesting
[[uid=830lw9dr]] subject. I never think of it myself.
[[uid=830lw9ds]] 
[[uid=830lw9dt]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9dw]] Very natural, I am sure. That will do,
[[uid=830lw9dx]] Lane, thank you.
[[uid=830lw9dy]] 
[[uid=830lw9dz]] LANE.
[[uid=830lw9f0]] Thank you, sir. [Lane goes out.]
[[uid=830lw9f1]] 
[[uid=830lw9f2]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9f3]] Lane’s views on marriage seem somewhat
[[uid=830lw9f4]] lax. Really, if the lower orders don’t
[[uid=830lw9f5]] set us a good example, what on earth is
[[uid=830lw9f6]] the use of them? They seem, as a class,
[[uid=830lw9f7]] to have absolutely no sense of moral
[[uid=830lw9f8]] responsibility.
[[uid=830lw9f9]] 
[[uid=830lw9fb]] [Enter Lane.]
[[uid=830lw9fc]] 
[[uid=830lw9fd]] LANE.
[[uid=830lw9ff]] Mr. Ernest Worthing.
[[uid=830lw9fg]] 
[[uid=830lw9fh]] [Enter Jack.] [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9fj]] 
[[uid=830lw9fk]] [Lane goes out.]
[[uid=830lw9fl]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9fm]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9fn]] How are you, my dear Ernest? What
[[uid=830lw9fp]] brings you up to town?
[[uid=830lw9fq]]  [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9fr]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9fs]] Oh, pleasure, pleasure! What else [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9ft]] should bring one anywhere? Eating as
[[uid=830lw9fw]] usual, I see, Algy!
[[uid=830lw9fx]] 
[[uid=830lw9fy]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9fz]] [Stiffly.] I believe it is customary in
[[uid=830lw9g0]] good society to take some slight
[[uid=830lw9g1]] refreshment at five o’clock. Where have [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9g2]] you been since last Thursday?
[[uid=830lw9g3]] 
[[uid=830lw9g4]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9g5]] [Sitting down on the sofa.] In the
[[uid=830lw9g6]] country.
[[uid=830lw9g7]] 
[[uid=830lw9g8]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9g9]] What on earth do you do there?
[[uid=830lw9gb]] 
[[uid=830lw9gc]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9gd]] [Pulling off his gloves.] When one is [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9gf]] in town one amuses oneself. When one is
[[uid=830lw9gg]] in the country one amuses other people.
[[uid=830lw9gh]] It is excessively boring.
[[uid=830lw9gj]] 
[[uid=830lw9gk]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9gl]] And who are the people you amuse?
[[uid=830lw9gm]] 
[[uid=830lw9gn]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9gp]] [Airily.] Oh, neighbours, neighbours.
[[uid=830lw9gq]] 
[[uid=830lw9gr]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9gs]] Got nice neighbours in your part of [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9gt]] Shropshire?
[[uid=830lw9gw]] 
[[uid=830lw9gx]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9gy]] Perfectly horrid! Never speak to one of
[[uid=830lw9gz]] them.
[[uid=830lw9h0]] 
[[uid=830lw9h1]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9h2]] How immensely you must amuse them!
[[uid=830lw9h3]] [Goes over and takes sandwich.] By the
[[uid=830lw9h4]] way, Shropshire is your county, is it
[[uid=830lw9h5]] not?
[[uid=830lw9h6]] 
[[uid=830lw9h7]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9h8]] Eh? Shropshire? Yes, of course. Hallo!
[[uid=830lw9h9]] Why all these cups? Why cucumber
[[uid=830lw9hb]] sandwiches? Why such reckless [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9hc]] extravagance in one so young? Who is
[[uid=830lw9hd]] coming to tea?
[[uid=830lw9hf]] 
[[uid=830lw9hg]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9hh]] Oh! merely Aunt Augusta and Gwendolen.
[[uid=830lw9hj]] 
[[uid=830lw9hk]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9hl]] How perfectly delightful!
[[uid=830lw9hm]] 
[[uid=830lw9hn]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9hp]] Yes, that is all very well; but I am
[[uid=830lw9hq]] afraid Aunt Augusta won’t quite approve
[[uid=830lw9hr]] of your being here.
[[uid=830lw9hs]] 
[[uid=830lw9ht]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9hw]] May I ask why?
[[uid=830lw9hx]] 
[[uid=830lw9hy]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9hz]] My dear fellow, the way you flirt with
[[uid=830lw9j0]] Gwendolen is perfectly disgraceful. It
[[uid=830lw9j1]] is almost as bad as the way Gwendolen
[[uid=830lw9j2]] flirts with you.
[[uid=830lw9j3]] 
[[uid=830lw9j4]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9j5]] I am in love with Gwendolen. I have
[[uid=830lw9j6]] come up to town expressly to propose to
[[uid=830lw9j7]] her.
[[uid=830lw9j8]] 
[[uid=830lw9j9]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9jb]] I thought you had come up for pleasure?
[[uid=830lw9jc]] . . . I call that business.
[[uid=830lw9jd]] 
[[uid=830lw9jf]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9jg]] How utterly unromantic you are!
[[uid=830lw9jh]] 
[[uid=830lw9jj]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9jk]] I really don’t see anything romantic in
[[uid=830lw9jl]] proposing. It is very romantic to be in
[[uid=830lw9jm]] love. But there is nothing romantic
[[uid=830lw9jn]] about a definite proposal. Why, one may
[[uid=830lw9jp]] be accepted. One usually is, I believe.
[[uid=830lw9jq]] Then the excitement is all over. The
[[uid=830lw9jr]] very essence of romance is uncertainty.
[[uid=830lw9js]] If ever I get married, I’ll certainly
[[uid=830lw9jt]] try to forget the fact.
[[uid=830lw9jw]] 
[[uid=830lw9jx]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9jy]] I have no doubt about that, dear Algy.
[[uid=830lw9jz]] The Divorce Court was specially
[[uid=830lw9k0]] invented for people whose memories are
[[uid=830lw9k1]] so curiously constituted.
[[uid=830lw9k2]] 
[[uid=830lw9k3]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9k4]] Oh! there is no use speculating on that
[[uid=830lw9k5]] subject. Divorces are made in
[[uid=830lw9k6]] Heaven—[Jack puts out his hand to take
[[uid=830lw9k7]] a sandwich. Algernon at once
[[uid=830lw9k8]] interferes.] Please don’t touch the
[[uid=830lw9k9]] cucumber sandwiches. They are ordered [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9kb]] specially for Aunt Augusta. [Takes one
[[uid=830lw9kc]] and eats it.]
[[uid=830lw9kd]] 
[[uid=830lw9kf]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9kg]] Well, you have been eating them all the
[[uid=830lw9kh]] time.
[[uid=830lw9kj]] 
[[uid=830lw9kk]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9kl]] That is quite a different matter. She
[[uid=830lw9km]] is my aunt. [Takes plate from below.]
[[uid=830lw9kn]] Have some bread and butter. The bread
[[uid=830lw9kp]] and butter is for Gwendolen. Gwendolen
[[uid=830lw9kq]] is devoted to bread and butter.
[[uid=830lw9kr]] 
[[uid=830lw9ks]] JACK. [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9kt]] [Advancing to table and helping
[[uid=830lw9kw]] himself.] And very good bread and
[[uid=830lw9kx]] butter it is too.
[[uid=830lw9ky]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9kz]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9l0]] Well, my dear fellow, you need not eat
[[uid=830lw9l1]] as if you were going to eat it all. You
[[uid=830lw9l2]] behave as if you were married to her
[[uid=830lw9l3]] already. You are not married to her
[[uid=830lw9l4]] already, and I don’t think you ever [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9l5]] will be.
[[uid=830lw9l6]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9l7]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9l8]] Why on earth do you say that?
[[uid=830lw9l9]] 
[[uid=830lw9lb]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9lc]] Well, in the first place girls never
[[uid=830lw9ld]] marry the men they flirt with. Girls
[[uid=830lw9lf]] don’t think it right.
[[uid=830lw9lg]] 
[[uid=830lw9lh]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9lj]] Oh, that is nonsense!
[[uid=830lw9lk]] 
[[uid=830lw9ll]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9lm]] It isn’t. It is a great truth. It
[[uid=830lw9ln]] accounts for the extraordinary number
[[uid=830lw9lp]] of bachelors that one sees all over the
[[uid=830lw9lq]] place. In the second place, I don’t
[[uid=830lw9lr]] give my consent.
[[uid=830lw9ls]] 
[[uid=830lw9lt]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9lw]] Your consent!
[[uid=830lw9lx]] 
[[uid=830lw9ly]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9lz]] My dear fellow, Gwendolen is my first [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9m0]] cousin. And before I allow you to marry
[[uid=830lw9m1]] her, you will have to clear up the
[[uid=830lw9m2]] whole question of Cecily. [Rings bell.]
[[uid=830lw9m3]] 
[[uid=830lw9m4]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9m5]] Cecily! What on earth do you mean? What
[[uid=830lw9m6]] do you mean, Algy, by Cecily! I don’t
[[uid=830lw9m7]] know any one of the name of Cecily.
[[uid=830lw9m8]] 
[[uid=830lw9m9]] [Enter Lane.] [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9mb]] 
[[uid=830lw9mc]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9md]] Bring me that cigarette case Mr.
[[uid=830lw9mf]] Worthing left in the smoking-room the
[[uid=830lw9mg]] last time he dined here.
[[uid=830lw9mh]] 
[[uid=830lw9mj]] LANE.
[[uid=830lw9mk]] Yes, sir. [Lane goes out.]
[[uid=830lw9ml]] 
[[uid=830lw9mm]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9mn]] Do you mean to say you have had my
[[uid=830lw9mp]] cigarette case all this time? I wish to [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9mq]] goodness you had let me know. I have
[[uid=830lw9mr]] been writing frantic letters to
[[uid=830lw9ms]] Scotland Yard about it. I was very
[[uid=830lw9mt]] nearly offering a large reward.
[[uid=830lw9mw]] 
[[uid=830lw9mx]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9my]] Well, I wish you would offer one. I
[[uid=830lw9mz]] happen to be more than usually hard up.
[[uid=830lw9n0]] 
[[uid=830lw9n1]] JACK. [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9n2]] There is no good offering a large
[[uid=830lw9n3]] reward now that the thing is found.
[[uid=830lw9n4]] 
[[uid=830lw9n5]] [Enter Lane with the cigarette case on
[[uid=830lw9n6]] a salver. Algernon takes it at once.
[[uid=830lw9n7]] Lane goes out.]
[[uid=830lw9n8]] 
[[uid=830lw9n9]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9nb]] I think that is rather mean of you,
[[uid=830lw9nc]] Ernest, I must say. [Opens case and
[[uid=830lw9nd]] examines it.] However, it makes no
[[uid=830lw9nf]] matter, for, now that I look at the
[[uid=830lw9ng]] inscription inside, I find that the
[[uid=830lw9nh]] thing isn’t yours after all.
[[uid=830lw9nj]] 
[[uid=830lw9nk]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9nl]] Of course it’s mine. [Moving to him.]
[[uid=830lw9nm]] You have seen me with it a hundred
[[uid=830lw9nn]] times, and you have no right whatsoever
[[uid=830lw9np]] to read what is written inside. It is a
[[uid=830lw9nq]] very ungentlemanly thing to read a
[[uid=830lw9nr]] private cigarette case.
[[uid=830lw9ns]] 
[[uid=830lw9nt]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9nw]] Oh! it is absurd to have a hard and
[[uid=830lw9nx]] fast rule about what one should read
[[uid=830lw9ny]] and what one shouldn’t. More than half
[[uid=830lw9nz]] of modern culture depends on what one
[[uid=830lw9p0]] shouldn’t read.
[[uid=830lw9p1]] 
[[uid=830lw9p2]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9p3]] I am quite aware of the fact, and I
[[uid=830lw9p4]] don’t propose to discuss modern
[[uid=830lw9p5]] culture. It isn’t the sort of thing one
[[uid=830lw9p6]] should talk of in private. I simply
[[uid=830lw9p7]] want my cigarette case back.
[[uid=830lw9p8]] 
[[uid=830lw9p9]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9pb]] Yes; but this isn’t your cigarette
[[uid=830lw9pc]] case. This cigarette case is a present [[attitudeInstr]] [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9pd]] from some one of the name of Cecily,
[[uid=830lw9pf]] and you said you didn’t know any one of
[[uid=830lw9pg]] that name.
[[uid=830lw9ph]] 
[[uid=830lw9pj]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9pk]] Well, if you want to know, Cecily
[[uid=830lw9pl]] happens to be my aunt.
[[uid=830lw9pm]] 
[[uid=830lw9pn]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9pp]] Your aunt!
[[uid=830lw9pq]] 
[[uid=830lw9pr]] JACK. [[attitudeInstr]] [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9ps]] Yes. Charming old lady she is, too.
[[uid=830lw9pt]] Lives at Tunbridge Wells. Just give it
[[uid=830lw9pw]] back to me, Algy.
[[uid=830lw9px]] 
[[uid=830lw9py]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9pz]] [Retreating to back of sofa.] But why
[[uid=830lw9q0]] does she call herself little Cecily if
[[uid=830lw9q1]] she is your aunt and lives at Tunbridge
[[uid=830lw9q2]] Wells? [Reading.] ‘From little Cecily
[[uid=830lw9q3]] with her fondest love.’
[[uid=830lw9q4]]  [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9q5]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9q6]] [Moving to sofa and kneeling upon it.]
[[uid=830lw9q7]] My dear fellow, what on earth is there
[[uid=830lw9q8]] in that? Some aunts are tall, some
[[uid=830lw9q9]] aunts are not tall. That is a matter
[[uid=830lw9qb]] that surely an aunt may be allowed to
[[uid=830lw9qc]] decide for herself. You seem to think
[[uid=830lw9qd]] that every aunt should be exactly like
[[uid=830lw9qf]] your aunt! That is absurd! For Heaven’s
[[uid=830lw9qg]] sake give me back my cigarette case.
[[uid=830lw9qh]] [Follows Algernon round the room.]
[[uid=830lw9qj]]  [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9qk]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9ql]] Yes. But why does your aunt call you
[[uid=830lw9qm]] her uncle? ‘From little Cecily, with
[[uid=830lw9qn]] her fondest love to her dear Uncle
[[uid=830lw9qp]] Jack.’ There is no objection, I admit,
[[uid=830lw9qq]] to an aunt being a small aunt, but why [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9qr]] an aunt, no matter what her size may
[[uid=830lw9qs]] be, should call her own nephew her
[[uid=830lw9qt]] uncle, I can’t quite make out. Besides,
[[uid=830lw9qw]] your name isn’t Jack at all; it is
[[uid=830lw9qx]] Ernest.
[[uid=830lw9qy]] 
[[uid=830lw9qz]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9r0]] It isn’t Ernest; it’s Jack.
[[uid=830lw9r1]] 
[[uid=830lw9r2]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9r3]] You have always told me it was Ernest.
[[uid=830lw9r4]] I have introduced you to every one as [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9r5]] Ernest. You answer to the name of
[[uid=830lw9r6]] Ernest. You look as if your name was
[[uid=830lw9r7]] Ernest. You are the most
[[uid=830lw9r8]] earnest-looking person I ever saw in my
[[uid=830lw9r9]] life. It is perfectly absurd your
[[uid=830lw9rb]] saying that your name isn’t Ernest.
[[uid=830lw9rc]] It’s on your cards. Here is one of
[[uid=830lw9rd]] them. [Taking it from case.] ‘Mr.
[[uid=830lw9rf]] Ernest Worthing, B. 4, The Albany.’
[[uid=830lw9rg]] I’ll keep this as a proof that your
[[uid=830lw9rh]] name is Ernest if ever you attempt to
[[uid=830lw9rj]] deny it to me, or to Gwendolen, or to
[[uid=830lw9rk]] any one else. [Puts the card in his
[[uid=830lw9rl]] pocket.] [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9rm]] 
[[uid=830lw9rn]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9rp]] Well, my name is Ernest in town and
[[uid=830lw9rq]] Jack in the country, and the cigarette
[[uid=830lw9rr]] case was given to me in the country.
[[uid=830lw9rs]] 
[[uid=830lw9rt]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9rw]] Yes, but that does not account for the
[[uid=830lw9rx]] fact that your small Aunt Cecily, who
[[uid=830lw9ry]] lives at Tunbridge Wells, calls you her
[[uid=830lw9rz]] dear uncle. Come, old boy, you had much
[[uid=830lw9s0]] better have the thing out at once.
[[uid=830lw9s1]] 
[[uid=830lw9s2]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9s3]] My dear Algy, you talk exactly as if
[[uid=830lw9s4]] you were a dentist. It is very vulgar
[[uid=830lw9s5]] to talk like a dentist when one isn’t a
[[uid=830lw9s6]] dentist. It produces a false
[[uid=830lw9s7]] impression.
[[uid=830lw9s8]] 
[[uid=830lw9s9]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9sb]] Well, that is exactly what dentists
[[uid=830lw9sc]] always do. Now, go on! Tell me the
[[uid=830lw9sd]] whole thing. I may mention that I have
[[uid=830lw9sf]] always suspected you of being a
[[uid=830lw9sg]] confirmed and secret Bunburyist; and I
[[uid=830lw9sh]] am quite sure of it now.
[[uid=830lw9sj]] 
[[uid=830lw9sk]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9sl]] Bunburyist? What on earth do you mean
[[uid=830lw9sm]] by a Bunburyist?
[[uid=830lw9sn]] 
[[uid=830lw9sp]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9sq]] I’ll reveal to you the meaning of that
[[uid=830lw9sr]] incomparable expression as soon as you
[[uid=830lw9ss]] are kind enough to inform me why you
[[uid=830lw9st]] are Ernest in town and Jack in the
[[uid=830lw9sw]] country.
[[uid=830lw9sx]] 
[[uid=830lw9sy]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9sz]] Well, produce my cigarette case first.
[[uid=830lw9t0]] 
[[uid=830lw9t1]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9t2]] Here it is. [Hands cigarette case.] Now
[[uid=830lw9t3]] produce your explanation, and pray make [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9t4]] it improbable. [Sits on sofa.]
[[uid=830lw9t5]] 
[[uid=830lw9t6]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9t7]] My dear fellow, there is nothing
[[uid=830lw9t8]] improbable about my explanation at all.
[[uid=830lw9t9]] In fact it’s perfectly ordinary. Old
[[uid=830lw9tb]] Mr. Thomas Cardew, who adopted me when
[[uid=830lw9tc]] I was a little boy, made me in his will
[[uid=830lw9td]] guardian to his grand-daughter, Miss
[[uid=830lw9tf]] Cecily Cardew. Cecily, who addresses me
[[uid=830lw9tg]] as her uncle from motives of respect
[[uid=830lw9th]] that you could not possibly appreciate,
[[uid=830lw9tj]] lives at my place in the country under [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9tk]] the charge of her admirable governess,
[[uid=830lw9tl]] Miss Prism.
[[uid=830lw9tm]] 
[[uid=830lw9tn]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9tp]] Where is that place in the country, by [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9tq]] the way?
[[uid=830lw9tr]] 
[[uid=830lw9ts]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9tt]] That is nothing to you, dear boy. You [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9tw]] are not going to be invited . . . I may
[[uid=830lw9tx]] tell you candidly that the place is not
[[uid=830lw9ty]] in Shropshire.
[[uid=830lw9tz]] 
[[uid=830lw9w0]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9w1]] I suspected that, my dear fellow! I
[[uid=830lw9w2]] have Bunburyed all over Shropshire on
[[uid=830lw9w3]] two separate occasions. Now, go on. Why
[[uid=830lw9w4]] are you Ernest in town and Jack in the
[[uid=830lw9w5]] country?
[[uid=830lw9w6]] 
[[uid=830lw9w7]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9w8]] My dear Algy, I don’t know whether you
[[uid=830lw9w9]] will be able to understand my real
[[uid=830lw9wb]] motives. You are hardly serious enough.
[[uid=830lw9wc]] When one is placed in the position of
[[uid=830lw9wd]] guardian, one has to adopt a very high
[[uid=830lw9wf]] moral tone on all subjects. It’s one’s
[[uid=830lw9wg]] duty to do so. And as a high moral tone
[[uid=830lw9wh]] can hardly be said to conduce very much
[[uid=830lw9wj]] to either one’s health or one’s
[[uid=830lw9wk]] happiness, in order to get up to town I
[[uid=830lw9wl]] have always pretended to have a younger
[[uid=830lw9wm]] brother of the name of Ernest, who
[[uid=830lw9wn]] lives in the Albany, and gets into the
[[uid=830lw9wp]] most dreadful scrapes. That, my dear
[[uid=830lw9wq]] Algy, is the whole truth pure and
[[uid=830lw9wr]] simple.
[[uid=830lw9ws]] 
[[uid=830lw9wt]] ALGERNON. [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9ww]] The truth is rarely pure and never
[[uid=830lw9wx]] simple. Modern life would be very
[[uid=830lw9wy]] tedious if it were either, and modern
[[uid=830lw9wz]] literature a complete impossibility!
[[uid=830lw9x0]] 
[[uid=830lw9x1]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9x2]] That wouldn’t be at all a bad thing.
[[uid=830lw9x3]] 
[[uid=830lw9x4]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9x5]] Literary criticism is not your forte,
[[uid=830lw9x6]] my dear fellow. Don’t try it. You
[[uid=830lw9x7]] should leave that to people who haven’t
[[uid=830lw9x8]] been at a University. They do it so
[[uid=830lw9x9]] well in the daily papers. What you
[[uid=830lw9xb]] really are is a Bunburyist. I was quite
[[uid=830lw9xc]] right in saying you were a Bunburyist. [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9xd]] You are one of the most advanced
[[uid=830lw9xf]] Bunburyists I know.
[[uid=830lw9xg]] 
[[uid=830lw9xh]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9xj]] What on earth do you mean?
[[uid=830lw9xk]] 
[[uid=830lw9xl]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9xm]] You have invented a very useful younger
[[uid=830lw9xn]] brother called Ernest, in order that
[[uid=830lw9xp]] you may be able to come up to town as
[[uid=830lw9xq]] often as you like. I have invented an [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9xr]] invaluable permanent invalid called
[[uid=830lw9xs]] Bunbury, in order that I may be able to
[[uid=830lw9xt]] go down into the country whenever I
[[uid=830lw9xw]] choose. Bunbury is perfectly
[[uid=830lw9xx]] invaluable. If it wasn’t for Bunbury’s
[[uid=830lw9xy]] extraordinary bad health, for instance,
[[uid=830lw9xz]] I wouldn’t be able to dine with you at
[[uid=830lw9y0]] Willis’s to-night, for I have been
[[uid=830lw9y1]] really engaged to Aunt Augusta for more
[[uid=830lw9y2]] than a week.
[[uid=830lw9y3]] 
[[uid=830lw9y4]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9y5]] I haven’t asked you to dine with me
[[uid=830lw9y6]] anywhere to-night.
[[uid=830lw9y7]] 
[[uid=830lw9y8]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9y9]] I know. You are absurdly careless about
[[uid=830lw9yb]] sending out invitations. It is very
[[uid=830lw9yc]] foolish of you. Nothing annoys people
[[uid=830lw9yd]] so much as not receiving invitations.
[[uid=830lw9yf]] 
[[uid=830lw9yg]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9yh]] You had much better dine with your Aunt
[[uid=830lw9yj]] Augusta.
[[uid=830lw9yk]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9yl]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9ym]] I haven’t the smallest intention of
[[uid=830lw9yn]] doing anything of the kind. To begin
[[uid=830lw9yp]] with, I dined there on Monday, and once
[[uid=830lw9yq]] a week is quite enough to dine with
[[uid=830lw9yr]] one’s own relations. In the second
[[uid=830lw9ys]] place, whenever I do dine there I am
[[uid=830lw9yt]] always treated as a member of the [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9yw]] family, and sent down with either no
[[uid=830lw9yx]] woman at all, or two. In the third
[[uid=830lw9yy]] place, I know perfectly well whom she [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9yz]] will place me next to, to-night. She
[[uid=830lw9z0]] will place me next Mary Farquhar, who
[[uid=830lw9z1]] always flirts with her own husband
[[uid=830lw9z2]] across the dinner-table. That is not
[[uid=830lw9z3]] very pleasant. Indeed, it is not even
[[uid=830lw9z4]] decent . . . and that sort of thing is
[[uid=830lw9z5]] enormously on the increase. The amount
[[uid=830lw9z6]] of women in London who flirt with their
[[uid=830lw9z7]] own husbands is perfectly scandalous.
[[uid=830lw9z8]] It looks so bad. It is simply washing
[[uid=830lw9z9]] one’s clean linen in public. Besides,
[[uid=830lw9zb]] now that I know you to be a confirmed
[[uid=830lw9zc]] Bunburyist I naturally want to talk to
[[uid=830lw9zd]] you about Bunburying. I want to tell
[[uid=830lw9zf]] you the rules.
[[uid=830lw9zg]] 
[[uid=830lw9zh]] JACK.
[[uid=830lw9zj]] I’m not a Bunburyist at all. If
[[uid=830lw9zk]] Gwendolen accepts me, I am going to
[[uid=830lw9zl]] kill my brother, indeed I think I’ll
[[uid=830lw9zm]] kill him in any case. Cecily is a
[[uid=830lw9zn]] little too much interested in him. It
[[uid=830lw9zp]] is rather a bore. So I am going to get
[[uid=830lw9zq]] rid of Ernest. And I strongly advise [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lw9zr]] you to do the same with Mr. . . . with
[[uid=830lw9zs]] your invalid friend who has the absurd
[[uid=830lw9zt]] name.
[[uid=830lw9zw]] 
[[uid=830lw9zx]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lw9zy]] Nothing will induce me to part with [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lw9zz]] Bunbury, and if you ever get married,
[[uid=830lwb00]] which seems to me extremely
[[uid=830lwb01]] problematic, you will be very glad to
[[uid=830lwb02]] know Bunbury. A man who marries without
[[uid=830lwb03]] knowing Bunbury has a very tedious time [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwb04]] of it.
[[uid=830lwb05]] 
[[uid=830lwb06]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwb07]] That is nonsense. If I marry a charming
[[uid=830lwb08]] girl like Gwendolen, and she is the
[[uid=830lwb09]] only girl I ever saw in my life that I
[[uid=830lwb0b]] would marry, I certainly won’t want to
[[uid=830lwb0c]] know Bunbury.
[[uid=830lwb0d]] 
[[uid=830lwb0f]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwb0g]] Then your wife will. You don’t seem to
[[uid=830lwb0h]] realise, that in married life three is [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwb0j]] company and two is none.
[[uid=830lwb0k]] 
[[uid=830lwb0l]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwb0m]] [Sententiously.] That, my dear young
[[uid=830lwb0n]] friend, is the theory that the corrupt
[[uid=830lwb0p]] French Drama has been propounding for
[[uid=830lwb0q]] the last fifty years.
[[uid=830lwb0r]] 
[[uid=830lwb0s]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwb0t]] Yes; and that the happy English home
[[uid=830lwb0w]] has proved in half the time.
[[uid=830lwb0x]]  [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwb0y]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwb0z]] For heaven’s sake, don’t try to be
[[uid=830lwb10]] cynical. It’s perfectly easy to be
[[uid=830lwb11]] cynical.
[[uid=830lwb12]] 
[[uid=830lwb13]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwb14]] My dear fellow, it isn’t easy to be
[[uid=830lwb15]] anything nowadays. There’s such a lot
[[uid=830lwb16]] of beastly competition about. [The
[[uid=830lwb17]] sound of an electric bell is heard.]
[[uid=830lwb18]] Ah! that must be Aunt Augusta. Only
[[uid=830lwb19]] relatives, or creditors, ever ring in
