[[uid=830lwb5b]] them.
[[uid=830lwb5c]] 
[[uid=830lwb5d]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwb5f]] I am afraid, Aunt Augusta, I shall have [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwb5g]] to give up the pleasure of dining with
[[uid=830lwb5h]] you to-night after all. [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwb5j]]  [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwb5k]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwb5l]] [Frowning.] I hope not, Algernon. It
[[uid=830lwb5m]] would put my table completely out. Your
[[uid=830lwb5n]] uncle would have to dine upstairs.
[[uid=830lwb5p]] Fortunately he is accustomed to that.
[[uid=830lwb5q]] 
[[uid=830lwb5r]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwb5s]] It is a great bore, and, I need hardly
[[uid=830lwb5t]] say, a terrible disappointment to me,
[[uid=830lwb5w]] but the fact is I have just had a
[[uid=830lwb5x]] telegram to say that my poor friend
[[uid=830lwb5y]] Bunbury is very ill again. [Exchanges
[[uid=830lwb5z]] glances with Jack.] They seem to think
[[uid=830lwb60]] I should be with him.
[[uid=830lwb61]] 
[[uid=830lwb62]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwb63]] It is very strange. This Mr. Bunbury
[[uid=830lwb64]] seems to suffer from curiously bad
[[uid=830lwb65]] health.
[[uid=830lwb66]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwb67]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwb68]] Yes; poor Bunbury is a dreadful
[[uid=830lwb69]] invalid.
[[uid=830lwb6b]] 
[[uid=830lwb6c]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwb6d]] Well, I must say, Algernon, that I
[[uid=830lwb6f]] think it is high time that Mr. Bunbury
[[uid=830lwb6g]] made up his mind whether he was going
[[uid=830lwb6h]] to live or to die. This
[[uid=830lwb6j]] shilly-shallying with the question is
[[uid=830lwb6k]] absurd. Nor do I in any way approve of
[[uid=830lwb6l]] the modern sympathy with invalids. I
[[uid=830lwb6m]] consider it morbid. Illness of any kind
[[uid=830lwb6n]] is hardly a thing to be encouraged in
