[[uid=830lwb80]] sounds a thoroughly respectable
[[uid=830lwb81]] language, and indeed, I believe is so.
[[uid=830lwb82]] Gwendolen, you will accompany me.
[[uid=830lwb83]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwb84]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwb85]] Certainly, mamma.
[[uid=830lwb86]] 
[[uid=830lwb87]] [Lady Bracknell and Algernon go into
[[uid=830lwb88]] the music-room, Gwendolen remains
[[uid=830lwb89]] behind.]
[[uid=830lwb8b]] 
[[uid=830lwb8c]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwb8d]] Charming day it has been, Miss Fairfax.
[[uid=830lwb8f]] 
[[uid=830lwb8g]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwb8h]] Pray don’t talk to me about the
[[uid=830lwb8j]] weather, Mr. Worthing. Whenever people
[[uid=830lwb8k]] talk to me about the weather, I always
[[uid=830lwb8l]] feel quite certain that they mean
[[uid=830lwb8m]] something else. And that makes me so
[[uid=830lwb8n]] nervous.
[[uid=830lwb8p]] 
[[uid=830lwb8q]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwb8r]] I do mean something else.
[[uid=830lwb8s]] 
[[uid=830lwb8t]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwb8w]] I thought so. In fact, I am never
[[uid=830lwb8x]] wrong.
[[uid=830lwb8y]] 
[[uid=830lwb8z]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwb90]] And I would like to be allowed to take
[[uid=830lwb91]] advantage of Lady Bracknell’s temporary
[[uid=830lwb92]] absence . . .
[[uid=830lwb93]] 
[[uid=830lwb94]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwb95]] I would certainly advise you to do so.
[[uid=830lwb96]] Mamma has a way of coming back suddenly
[[uid=830lwb97]] into a room that I have often had to
[[uid=830lwb98]] speak to her about.
[[uid=830lwb99]] 
[[uid=830lwb9b]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwb9c]] [Nervously.] Miss Fairfax, ever since I
[[uid=830lwb9d]] met you I have admired you more than
[[uid=830lwb9f]] any girl . . . I have ever met since .
[[uid=830lwb9g]] . . I met you.
[[uid=830lwb9h]] 
[[uid=830lwb9j]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwb9k]] Yes, I am quite well aware of the fact.
[[uid=830lwb9l]] And I often wish that in public, at any
[[uid=830lwb9m]] rate, you had been more demonstrative.
[[uid=830lwb9n]] For me you have always had an
[[uid=830lwb9p]] irresistible fascination. Even before I
[[uid=830lwb9q]] met you I was far from indifferent to
[[uid=830lwb9r]] you. [Jack looks at her in amazement.]
[[uid=830lwb9s]] We live, as I hope you know, Mr.
[[uid=830lwb9t]] Worthing, in an age of ideals. The fact
[[uid=830lwb9w]] is constantly mentioned in the more
[[uid=830lwb9x]] expensive monthly magazines, and has
[[uid=830lwb9y]] reached the provincial pulpits, I am
[[uid=830lwb9z]] told; and my ideal has always been to
[[uid=830lwbb0]] love some one of the name of Ernest.
[[uid=830lwbb1]] There is something in that name that
[[uid=830lwbb2]] inspires absolute confidence. The
[[uid=830lwbb3]] moment Algernon first mentioned to me
[[uid=830lwbb4]] that he had a friend called Ernest, I
[[uid=830lwbb5]] knew I was destined to love you.
[[uid=830lwbb6]] 
[[uid=830lwbb7]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwbb8]] You really love me, Gwendolen?
[[uid=830lwbb9]] 
[[uid=830lwbbb]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwbbc]] Passionately!
[[uid=830lwbbd]] 
[[uid=830lwbbf]] JACK.
